dat$BSS_log <- log(dat$BSS_sum + 1)

Exploratory correlations

COPE subscales and SI

M<-cor(dat[c(cope.subscales,"BSS_log")], use = "pairwise.complete.obs")

corrplot(M, method="circle", order="hclust")

COPE subscales and SI (filtering on statistical significance)

Now we want to make a version that filters for significance. To do this, we need to define a function that calculates p-values.

# mat : is a matrix of data
# ... : further arguments to pass to the native R cor.test function
cor.mtest <- function(mat, ...) {
    mat <- as.matrix(mat)
    n <- ncol(mat)
    p.mat<- matrix(NA, n, n)
    diag(p.mat) <- 0
    for (i in 1:(n - 1)) {
        for (j in (i + 1):n) {
            tmp <- cor.test(mat[, i], mat[, j], ...)
            p.mat[i, j] <- p.mat[j, i] <- tmp$p.value
        }
    }
  colnames(p.mat) <- rownames(p.mat) <- colnames(mat)
  p.mat
}

And we use it to make our plot. Nonsignificant correlations (p>.05) how have an X drawn over them.

# matrix of the p-value of the correlation
p.mat <- cor.mtest(dat[c(cope.subscales,"BSS_log")])
corrplot(M, type="upper", order="hclust", 
         p.mat = p.mat, sig.level = 0.05,
         insig="pch", pch=4, pch.cex=1.5,
         pch.col=rgb(0,0,0,.5))

Multivariate analysis

Fit model.

fit <- stan_glm(BSS_log ~
                Age +
                marital +
                yr_edu +
                race +
                 FCESD + 
                 humor +
                 active.coping +
                 planning +
                 emotional.social.support +
                 positive.reinterpretation.and.growth +
                 behavioral.disengagement,
               iter=4000,
               cores=4,
               data=dat)

Plot 95% credible intervals, with 80% credible intervals shaded.

plot(fit, "areas", pars="beta", 
     prob_outer=.95, prob=.8)

For readability, replot without the absurdly uncertain variables:

plot(fit, "areas", 
     pars=c("Age","yr_edu","FCESD","humor","active.coping",
            "planning","emotional.social.support",
            "positive.reinterpretation.and.growth",
            "behavioral.disengagement"),
     prob_outer=.95, prob=.8)

Interpretation

Let’s think about what our model is saying. First of all, depression may not be the strongest predictor of suicidality in the sample, as some of the COPE subscales have large potential estimates. Let’s look at some of the COPE subscales in more detail. You can check out the complete measure and scoring instructions here.

Emotional Social Support

The emotional social support subscale is the only classically statistically significant COPE predictor in the model(–but PLEASE remember that filtering on statistical significance leads to overconfident expectations of replicability). The subscale consists of the following four items:

  • I discuss my feelings with someone
  • I try to get emotional support from friends or relatives
  • I get sympathy and understanding from someone
  • I talk to someone about how I feel

These are the specific kinds of coping strategies that may be associated with decreased suicidality even after controlling for depression.

Positive Reinterpretation and Growth

The positive reinterpretation and growth subscale is not classically statistically significant but the point estimate is even greater than the point estimate for emotional social support and it’s possible it has a strong ameliorative effect on suicidality. Here are the four items that compose this subscale:

  • I try to grow as a person as a result of the experience.
  • I try to see it in a different light, to make it seem more positive.
  • I look for something good in what is happening
  • I learn something from the experience.

Makes sense. These coping strategies are constructive and half of them are innately future-oriented.

Planning

Interestingly, planning may be associated with increased risk of suicidality. Let’s look at the items to figure out why this might be:

  • I make a plan of action
  • I try to come up with a strategy about what to do
  • I think about how I might best handle the problem
  • I think hard about what steps to take

Notice how none of these are action steps–at best they’re examples of “planning”, but they could also be described as “worrying”. It’s possible these kinds of strategies serve as (mild) proxies for anxiety.
